  "name": "Theater Tree: The Empty Space",
  "description": "A grammar of theater as embodied practice — not plays, but the art of making theater. From Stanislavski's emotional truth to Grotowski's holy actor, from Brecht's political interruption to Boal's liberation. Each practitioner is a node in a living tree whose roots reach back to Greek ritual and whose branches keep growing. Named for Peter Brook's insight: 'I can take any empty space and call it a bare stage.'\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Ancient Greek theater masks and vase paintings (5th century BCE). Commedia dell'arte engravings by Jacques Callot (1622). Victorian theatrical photographs and playbills. Constructivist stage designs by Meyerhold/Popova (1920s).",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "tags": ["theater", "embodiment", "performance", "acting", "directing", "ritual", "politics", "body"],
  "roots": ["western-philosophy", "embodiment", "liberation"],
  "shelves": ["wonder", "resilience"],
  "lineages": ["Akomolafe", "Andreotti"],
  "worldview": "dialectical",
  "grammars": [
    "https://github.com/PlayfulProcess/recursive.eco-schemas/tree/main/grammars/shakespeare-complete-works",
